ce:section.ce:para:
Thermally stimulated luminescence (TSL) is the phenomenon of the light emission during warming a previously irradiated substance with uniform heating rate. When a material is exposed to ionized radiation such as α, β, γ, X-rays and UV-rays or undergoes certain chemical reactions or mechanical stress, a certain percentage of the liberated charge carriers (electron and holes) may be trapped at certain imperfections in the lattice. A dosimetric research of a thermoluminescent material is based on a virtue knowledge of its kinetic parameters which quantitatively describes the trapping–emitting centers principal for the thermoluminescence emission. There are particular techniques to evaluate the trapping parameters such as the activation energy (E

                           a
                        ), the pre-exponential factor (s) and the order of kinetics (b) from TL glow curves [34,35].
